In .NET MAUI, you use the **lifecycle events mapper** in `MauiProgram.cs` via `ConfigureLifecycleEvents`:

```csharp
using Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents;

public static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()
{
    var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();
    builder.UseMauiApp<App>()
        .ConfigureLifecycleEvents(events =>
        {
#if ANDROID
            events.AddAndroid(android => android
                .OnPause(activity =>
                {
                    // runs when the activity is paused
                })
                .OnStop(activity =>
                {
                    // runs when the activity is no longer visible
                }));
#elif IOS
            events.AddiOS(ios => ios
                .DidEnterBackground(app =>
                {
                    // runs when the app enters background
                }));
#endif
        });

    return builder.Build();
}
```

**Key points:**

- **`ConfigureLifecycleEvents`** is the single cross-platform entry point; you branch per platform with `#if` directives.
- **Android** exposes `OnPause`, `OnStop`, `OnResume`, `OnDestroy`, etc. — mirroring the `Activity` lifecycle.
- **iOS** exposes `DidEnterBackground`, `WillEnterForeground`, `WillTerminate`, etc. — mirroring `UIApplicationDelegate`.
- Add the NuGet reference to `Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents` (included by default in MAUI projects).

This avoids overriding platform-specific `MainActivity` or `AppDelegate` classes and keeps all lifecycle logic in one place.
